[?2004l[?2004h>    - The string match module inspects packet data using Boyer-Moore algorithm
[?2004l[?2004h>    - If "Mozilla" is NOT found, traffic falls through to the DROP rules
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> 3. Why curl hangs:
[?2004l[?2004h>    - curl's default User-Agent is "curl/X.X.X", not "Mozilla/..."
[?2004l[?2004h>    - The string "Mozilla" is not present in curl's HTTP requests
[?2004l[?2004h>    - Traffic doesn't match the ACCEPT rule, hits the DROP rule instead
[?2004l[?2004h>    - TCP connection hangs because packets are silently dropped after the handshake
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> TECHNICAL ISSUE:
[?2004l[?2004h> The string matching approach is fundamentally flawed for access control:
[?2004l[?2004h> - It attempts to filter by User-Agent string in application-layer data
[?2004l[?2004h> - This breaks legitimate tools (curl, wget, scripts, APIs, monitoring tools)
[?2004l[?2004h> - String matching on packet payloads is unreliable and easily bypassed
[?2004l[?2004h> - It creates a false sense of security while blocking legitimate traffic
[?2004l[?2004h> 
[?2004l[?2004h> RECOMMENDATION:
[?2004l[?2004h> Remove the string-based filtering rules (7-10) and replace with proper access control:
[?2004l[?2004h> - Use source IP-based filtering if restricting access by origin
[?2004l[?2004h> - Implement rate limiting with the 'recent' or 'limit' modules at the netfilter level
[?2004l[?2004h> - Move application-layer filtering to the web server (nginx/apache) where it belongs
